Under MDR 2017/745, manufacturers have comprehensive post-market surveillance (PMS) and post-market clinical follow-up (PMCF) obligations designed to ensure the continued safety, performance, and benefit-risk acceptability of their devices throughout their lifecycle. Below is a structured analysis of these obligations, grounded exclusively in the provided regulatory context.

---

### 1. Post-Market Surveillance (PMS) Obligations
#### 1.1. Establishment and Maintenance of a PMS System
Manufacturers must plan, establish, document, implement, maintain, and update a PMS system for each device (**Article 83(1)**). This system must be:
- Proportionate to the risk class and appropriate for the device type;
- Integrated into the manufacturer’s quality management system (**Article 10(9)**);
- Suited to actively and systematically gather, record, and analyse data on the device’s quality, performance, and safety throughout its entire lifetime (**Article 83(2)**).

The PMS system must enable the manufacturer to:
- Draw necessary conclusions from the data;
- Determine, implement, and monitor preventive and corrective actions (**Article 83(2)**).

#### 1.2. Data Collection and Utilisation
The PMS system must collect and utilise data for the following purposes (**Article 83(3)**):
- Update the benefit-risk determination and improve risk management (**Annex I**, Chapter I);
- Update design and manufacturing information, instructions for use, and labelling;
- Update the clinical evaluation (**Article 61** and **Annex XIV**, Part A);
- Update the summary of safety and clinical performance (**Article 32(2)**(f)) for implantable and Class III devices;
- Identify needs for preventive, corrective, or field safety corrective actions;
- Identify options to improve usability, performance, and safety;
- Contribute to the PMS of other devices, where relevant;
- Detect and report trends in accordance with **Article 88**.

#### 1.3. PMS Plan
The PMS system must be based on a PMS plan, which is part of the technical documentation for all devices except custom-made devices (**Article 84** and **Annex III**, Section 1). The PMS plan must address:
- Collection and utilisation of available information, including:
 - Serious incidents, field safety corrective actions, and PSURs;
 - Non-serious incidents and undesirable side-effects;
 - Trend reporting data;
 - Relevant scientific literature, databases, and registers;
 - Feedback and complaints from users, distributors, and importers;
 - Publicly available information on similar devices (**Annex III**, point 1(a)).
- Proactive and systematic processes to collect and characterise device performance, including comparisons with similar products (**Annex III**, point 1(b), indent 9);
- Methods and processes to assess collected data (**Annex III**, point 1(b), indent 10);
- Indicators and threshold values for continuous reassessment of the benefit-risk analysis and risk management (**Annex III**, point 1(b), indent 11);
- Methods and protocols for investigating complaints, analysing market-related experience, and managing trend reporting (**Annex III**, point 1(b));
- Procedures for communication with competent authorities, notified bodies, economic operators, and users;
- Reference to procedures for fulfilling obligations under **Articles 83**, 84, and 86;
- Systematic procedures to identify and initiate appropriate measures, including corrective actions;
- Tools to trace and identify devices requiring corrective actions;
- A PMCF plan (as referred to in **Annex XIV**, Part B) or a justification for its non-applicability (**Annex III**, point 1(b), indent 14).

#### 1.4. PMS Reporting
- Class I Devices: Manufacturers must prepare a PMS report summarising the results and conclusions of PMS data analyses, including a rationale and description of any preventive or corrective actions taken. This report must be updated as necessary and made available to competent authorities upon request (**Article 85**).
- Higher-Risk Devices (Class IIa, IIb, III): Manufacturers must prepare Periodic Safety Update Reports (PSURs) in accordance with **Article 86**, which are submitted to notified bodies and, upon request, to competent authorities.

#### 1.5. Implementation of Corrective Actions
If the PMS system identifies a need for preventive or corrective actions, the manufacturer must:
- Implement appropriate measures;
- Inform competent authorities and, where applicable, the notified body (**Article 83(4)**);
- Report serious incidents or field safety corrective actions in accordance with **Article 87**.

---

### 2. Post-Market Clinical Follow-Up (PMCF) Obligations
#### 2.1. Purpose and Scope of PMCF
PMCF is a continuous process that updates the clinical evaluation (**Article 61** and **Annex XIV**, Part A) and is addressed in the manufacturer’s PMS plan (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 5). Its objectives are to:
- Confirm the safety and performance of the device throughout its expected lifetime;
- Ensure the continued acceptability of identified risks;
- Detect emerging risks based on factual evidence (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 5).

#### 2.2. PMCF Plan
PMCF must be performed pursuant to a documented PMCF plan, which specifies methods and procedures for proactively collecting and evaluating clinical data (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 6). The PMCF plan must include:
- General methods and procedures, such as:
 - Gathering clinical experience and user feedback;
 - Screening scientific literature and other clinical data sources (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 6.2(a));
- Specific methods and procedures, such as:
 - Evaluation of registers or PMCF studies (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 6.2(b));
- A rationale for the appropriateness of the chosen methods (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 6.2(c));
- Reference to relevant parts of the clinical evaluation report and risk management (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 6.2(d));
- Specific objectives to be addressed by the PMCF (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 6.2(e));
- Evaluation of clinical data relating to equivalent or similar devices (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 6.2(f));
- Reference to relevant common specifications (CS), harmonised standards, and guidance on PMCF (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 6.2(g));
- A detailed and justified time schedule for PMCF activities, including data analysis and reporting (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 6.2(h)).

The PMCF plan must aim to (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 6.1):
- Confirm the safety and performance of the device throughout its expected lifetime;
- Identify previously unknown side-effects and monitor identified side-effects and contraindications;
- Identify and analyse emergent risks based on factual evidence;
- Ensure the continued acceptability of the benefit-risk ratio (**Annex I**, Sections 1 and 9);
- Identify systematic misuse or off-label use to verify the intended purpose.

#### 2.3. PMCF Evaluation Report
The manufacturer must:
- Analyse the findings of the PMCF;
- Document the results in a PMCF evaluation report, which forms part of the clinical evaluation report and the technical documentation (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 7);
- Take the conclusions of the PMCF evaluation report into account for:
 - Updating the clinical evaluation (**Article 61** and **Annex XIV**, Part A);
 - Updating the risk management (**Annex I**, Section 3);
- Implement preventive and/or corrective measures if identified through PMCF (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 8).

#### 2.4. Integration with Clinical Evaluation
PMCF is an integral part of the clinical evaluation process (**Article 61(3)**). The clinical evaluation plan must include a clinical development plan, which outlines the progression from exploratory investigations (e.g., first-in-man studies) to confirmatory investigations (e.g., pivotal clinical investigations) and PMCF, with milestones and acceptance criteria (**Annex XIV**, Part A, point 1, indent 9).

---

### 3. Interaction Between PMS and PMCF
- PMCF is a subset of PMS, focusing specifically on the proactive collection and evaluation of clinical data to update the clinical evaluation (**Annex XIV**, Part B, point 5).
- The PMS plan must include a PMCF plan or a justification for its non-applicability (**Annex III**, point 1(b), indent 14).
- Data collected through PMCF feeds into the PMS system, which in turn informs updates to the clinical evaluation, risk management, and benefit-risk determination (**Article 83(3)**(a) and (c)).

---

### 4. Notified Body Involvement
For devices requiring notified body involvement (e.g., Class IIa, IIb, III, and implantable devices), the notified body must:
- Review the PMS and PMCF plans as part of the conformity assessment process (**Annex XI**, Part B, point 13);
- Conduct surveillance activities, including:
 - Annual surveillance audits of the manufacturer (**Annex VII**, point 4.10, indent 18);
 - In-depth review of the clinical evaluation, including updates based on PMS, PMCF, and relevant clinical literature (**Annex VII**, point 4.10, indent 18);
 - Screening of post-market information and vigilance data to assess the validity of existing certificates (**Annex VII**, point 4.10, indent 2-3).

---

### 5. Summary of Key Obligations
| Obligation | Applicable Provision | Key Requirements |
|------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| PMS System | **Article 83(1)**, **Article 10(9)** | Establish, maintain, and update a PMS system integrated into the QMS. |
| PMS Plan | **Article 84**, **Annex III** | Develop a PMS plan addressing data collection, assessment, and utilisation. |
| PMS Data Utilisation | **Article 83(3)** | Use PMS data to update benefit-risk determination, clinical evaluation, labelling, and risk management. |
| PMS Reporting | **Article 85**, **Article 86** | Prepare PMS reports (Class I) or PSURs (Class IIa, IIb, III). |
| PMCF Plan | **Annex XIV**, Part B, point 6 | Develop a PMCF plan with methods, objectives, and a time schedule. |
| PMCF Evaluation Report | **Annex XIV**, Part B, point 7 | Analyse PMCF findings and document results in a report. |
| Integration with Clinical Evaluation | **Article 61**, **Annex XIV**, Part A | Update clinical evaluation based on PMCF findings. |
| Notified Body Review | **Annex VII**, point 4.10, **Annex XI**, Part B | Ensure notified body reviews PMS/PMCF plans and conducts surveillance activities. |

---

### 6. Conclusion
Manufacturers must adopt a proactive, systematic, and risk-proportionate approach to PMS and PMCF under MDR 2017/745. The PMS system serves as the overarching framework for collecting and analysing data, while PMCF focuses specifically on clinical data to update the clinical evaluation. Both processes are continuous and iterative, ensuring that devices remain safe and effective throughout their lifecycle. Compliance requires documented plans, regular updates, and integration with risk management and clinical evaluation processes. For higher-risk devices, notified bodies play a critical role in reviewing and monitoring these activities.

